[ wetting agents ]
- 90g (/remainder of can) apple cider in sprayer
- 60g liquid smoke dilution (from 3.5g liquid smoke) in sprayer

[ rub ]
for a 650g rack:
- 5g smoked salt
- 5g coarse black pepper
- 1.8g (1 tsp) paprika
- 3g (1 tsp) garlic powder
- 2.3g (0.75) tsp onion powder
- 0.2g (0.25 tsp) cayenne
- 0.8g (0.75 tsp) dried thyme
- 0.75 tsp dried oregano

[ bbq sauce ]
- 65g apple cider vinegar
- 180g (0.75 cup) tomato sauce
- 65g apple cider
- 27g (0.75 tbsp) molasses
- 22g (1/6 cup) brown sug
- 2.8g (1 tsp) mustard powder
- 2.3g (0.75 tsp) garlic powder
- 5.5g (1 tsp) worcestershire sauce
- 2.4g (0.5 tsp) salt
- 0.7g (0.5 tsp) black pep
- 0.5g (0.5 tsp) cayenne (optional, for spice)

[ prep ]
- pat dry
- remove membrane
- spray with curing salt dilution
  - 2g into 60g water, then 10g diluted mix into another 60g water
- starting with salt then remainder of mix, apply rub
  - 2:1 meat:bone side
- refrigerate for 30 mins - 4 hours (overnight okay if no curing salt used)

[ sauce ]
- place all ingredients in saucepan and simmer for 45 mins (or until thickened)
- stir occasionally

[ cooking ]
- oven to 135°C
- place water-filled pan below to catch drippings
- spray with liquid smoke
- into oven on wire rack until surface temp reaches 65°C (roughly 1 hour)
  - drop temp to 120 if temp climbs too fast
- spray with apple cider then liquid smoke again
- back into oven until surface temp reaches 82°C (roughly another hour)
- repeat spray with cider then smoke
- back into oven until *core* temp reaches 96°C (roughly another hour)
- oven down to 120°C
- ribs onto foil + baking paper-lined tray, bone side up
- baste topside then bake for 10 mins
- flip and baste topside every 10 mins until ribs have a thick glaze (up to an hour)
- rest until core temp is down to 65°C
- slice and serve
